To use Google Places Autocomplete in a Chrome extension, you need to use the Maps JavaScript API within a content script or a pop-up page, ensuring you follow the Chrome extension Content Security Policy (CSP) and use an API key with appropriate restrictions. 
Prerequisites
Set up a Google Cloud Project: Go to the Google Cloud Console and create a new project.
Enable APIs: Enable the Maps JavaScript API and the Places API (or Places API (New)) for your project.
Get an API Key: Generate an API key under APIs & Services > Credentials. Restrict the key to your extension ID and website (if applicable) to prevent unauthorized use.
Set up billing: The Places API is a paid service, so you will need to enable billing for your project. 
Implementation Steps
The implementation method depends on where you want the autocomplete input to appear (either in the extension's pop-up or on a webpage via a content script). 
Option 1: In the Extension's Pop-up
This is the most straightforward method as the pop-up operates within the extension's environment, allowing for easy integration of the Google Maps script. 
manifest.json: Declare your pop-up and add the Content Security Policy (CSP) to allow Google's scripts.
json
{
  "manifest_version": 3,
  "name": "Places Autocomplete Extension",
  "version": "1.0",
  "action": {
    "default_popup": "popup.html",
    "default_icon": "icons/icon.png"
  },
  "permissions": ["activeTab", "scripting"],
  "content_security_policy": {
    "extension_pages": "script-src 'self' https://maps.googleapis.com; object-src 'self';"
  }
}
popup.html: Create an input element and load the Google Maps script with your API key and the places library.
html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Places Autocomplete</title>
  <script src="popup.js" defer></script>
</head>
<body>
  <input id="autocomplete" placeholder="Enter a place" type="text"/>
  <!-- Load the Maps JavaScript API -->
  <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com" async defer></script>
</body>
</html>
popup.js: Initialize the Autocomplete service once the script is loaded.
javascript
function initAutocomplete() {
  const input = document.getElementById("autocomplete");
  const autocomplete = new google.maps.places.Autocomplete(input);
  // Optional: Add listeners to handle place selection
  autocomplete.addListener("place_changed", () => {
    const place = autocomplete.getPlace();
    console.log(place.name, place.place_id);
  });
}

Option 2: On a Webpage (Content Script)
Content scripts run in the context of the webpage and cannot directly add the Google API <script> tag or access the google.maps object if the page doesn't already have it. You need to inject the script. 
manifest.json: Declare the content script.
json
{
  "manifest_version": 3,
  "name": "Places Autocomplete Content Script",
  "version": "1.0",
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": ["<all_urls>"],
      "js": ["content.js"]
    }
  ],
  "permissions": ["scripting"]
}
content.js: Inject the Google Maps script into the page's DOM. You may need to wait for a specific input field to appear on the page or create your own element.
javascript
// Function to inject the script
function injectGoogleMapsScript() {
  const script = document.createElement('script');
  script.src = 'https://maps.googleapis.com';
  script.async = true;
  script.defer = true;
  document.head.appendChild(script);
}

// Function to initialize Autocomplete (must be a global function on the page)
window.initializeAutocomplete = () => {
  const inputElement = document.getElementById('some-input-on-the-page'); // Target a specific input
  if (inputElement) {
    const autocomplete = new google.maps.places.Autocomplete(inputElement);
    // ... add listeners as in Option 1
  }
};

// Inject the script when the content script runs
injectGoogleMapsScript();

To use Google Places Autocomplete in a Chrome Extension side panel, enable the Places API in Google Cloud Console, configure your manifest.json for side_panel, and include the Maps JavaScript API in your sidepanel.html. Bind the google.maps.places.Autocomplete service to an input field in your JavaScript file to display suggestions. 
Implementation Steps
Enable API and Get Key:
Go to the Google Cloud Console and create a project.
Enable the Places API and Maps JavaScript API.
Generate an API key and restrict it to your extension's ID or relevant domain for security.
Configure Manifest (v3):
Add the sidePanel permission and set the default path for your HTML file.
json
{
  "name": "Places Autocomplete Panel",
  "version": "1.0",
  "manifest_version": 3,
  "permissions": ["sidePanel"],
  "side_panel": {
    "default_path": "sidepanel.html"
  },
  "background": {
    "service_worker": "service-worker.js"
  }
}
Create the Side Panel HTML:
Create sidepanel.html and add an input field.
html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Places Search</title>
  <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_API_KEY&libraries=places"></script>
  <script src="sidepanel.js" defer></script>
</head>
<body>
  <input type="text" id="autocomplete" placeholder="Enter a location" />
</body>
</html>
Initialize Autocomplete in JavaScript (sidepanel.js):
Initialize the Autocomplete service on your input element.
javascript
window.addEventListener('load', () => {
  const input = document.getElementById('autocomplete');
  const autocomplete = new google.maps.places.Autocomplete(input, {
    types: ['geocode'], // Or 'establishment'
  });

  autocomplete.addListener('place_changed', () => {
    const place = autocomplete.getPlace();
    console.log(place); // Handle the selected place details
  });
});

Best Practices for Side Panels
Use Session Tokens: Use sessionToken to group autocomplete requests with place details requests to reduce costs.
Styling: Customize the .pac-container CSS class to ensure the dropdown fits within the narrow side panel.
Restrict Results: Use locationBias or locationRestriction to narrow suggestions to a specific area, improving relevance for the user.

